K Means or Hierarchical clustering to find out the optimal no of clusters in the data¶

In [755]:
# For finding the optimal numbers of clusters in the data, we are using K Means method at first to 
# find out the total numbers of cluster formationb 
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

wc_ss=[]                      # Within Cluster Sum of Squares  
cluster_range = range(1,10)
for k in cluster_range:
    model1  = KMeans(n_clusters = k)
    model1.fit(dataset2)
    model1_predict = model1.predict(dataset2)
    wc_ss.append(model1.inertia_)
    
    
plt.plot(cluster_range,wc_ss,'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Within Cluster Sum of Squares')
plt.title('Selecting K value from the Elbow  diagram')
Out[755]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting K value from the Elbow  diagram')
In [756]:
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
wc_ss=[]                      # Within Cluster Sum of Squares  
cluster_range = range(1,10)
for k in cluster_range:
    model1  = KMeans(n_clusters = k)
    model1.fit(dataset2)
    model1_predict = model1.predict(dataset2)
    wc_ss.append(sum(np.min(cdist(dataset2,model1.cluster_centers_,'euclidean'),axis=1))/dataset2.shape[0])
    
plt.plot(cluster_range,wc_ss,'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Within Cluster Sum of Squares')
plt.title('Selecting K value from the Elbow  diagram')

X1 = small_car.drop('mpg', axis=1)
y1 = small_car[['mpg']]
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X1, y1, test_size=0.25, random_state=1)
regression_model1 = LinearRegression()
regression_model1.fit(X_train, y_train)
for idx, col_name in enumerate(X_train.columns):
    print("The coefficient for {} is {}".format(col_name, regression_model1.coef_[0][idx]))
intercept = regression_model1.intercept_[0]
print("The intercept for our model is {}".format(intercept))
print("Accuracy score for small car for training data:",regression_model1.score(X_train, y_train))
print("Accuracy score for small car for test data:",regression_model1.score(X_test, y_test))
